8. Package
A Package is a curated multi-destination product — for example, the Golden Triangle Nepal package might include Kathmandu, Pokhara, and Chitwan as three linked destinations, each with custom names, descriptions, and day allocations, combined under a single custom price, itinerary, and group discount structure.

Tip: Packages operate independently of the region hierarchy. A single package can span multiple regions and countries. The destinations within a package are linked via the package_destinations join table, which carries per-destination customisation fields.

8.1  Core Package Fields
Field	Type	Required	Description / Notes
id	uuid	Yes	Primary key.
title	string	Yes	Package name. 3–255 chars. (e.g. Golden Triangle Nepal)
slug	string	Yes	Unique URL slug.
description	text	No	Full package description.
totalDays	integer	No	Auto-computed OR manually set total trip duration.
basePrice	decimal(10,2)	No	Custom package price (overrides sum of individual product prices).
status	enum	No	Values: draft | published | archived. Default draft.
destinations	relation	No	Many-to-many via package_destinations join table (see below).
regionIds	uuid[]	No	Optional region tags for filtering.
highlights	string[]	No	Key selling points.
inclusions	string[]	No	What is included.
exclusions	string[]	No	What is not included.
itinerary	JSON[]	No	Combined day-by-day plan across all linked destinations.
sortOrder	integer	No	Display order.
createdAt	timestamp	—	Auto-set.
updatedAt	timestamp	—	Auto-updated.
deletedAt	timestamp	—	Soft delete.

8.2  Package Destinations Join Table (package_destinations)
This table links destinations to a package and allows full customisation of each destination's presentation within the package context. For example, 'Pokhara' might be labelled 'Lakeside Pokhara Experience' within the Golden Triangle package.

Field	Type	Required	Description / Notes
